			script: "When does each technique help? Batching: Use it when throughput matters more than latency. Batch size of four or eight often doubles throughput with modest latency increase. For background processing, research pipelines, or high-volume APIs, batching is essential. For real-time chat where every millisecond counts, use smaller batches or no batching. Concurrency: Use it when you serve multiple models or many concurrent users. Run two model instances on one GPU if memory allows. Scale out to multiple GPUs when a single GPU is saturated. Monitor GPU utilization—if it's below eighty percent, you have headroom for more concurrency. TensorRT: Use it when latency and cost are critical. The compilation step is one-time. The gains are permanent. For agent workloads, TensorRT can cut latency by twenty to forty percent. That directly improves user experience and reduces cost per request. Baseline first. Measure latency, throughput, and cost before optimizing. Then turn on batching and compare. Then add TensorRT and compare. The numbers will tell you what's worth it.",
