			script: "What does production monitoring look like? Latency tracking: Log every request's end-to-end latency. Track p50, p95, p99. Agent workloads have variable latency—more steps mean more time. But sudden spikes indicate problems: model slowdown, tool timeouts, or queue backup. Alert when p95 exceeds a threshold. Cost awareness: Log token usage per request. Agents consume more tokens than single-call systems. Track cost per request and cost per user. Set budgets and alert when you're trending over. Cost spikes often correlate with loops or runaway retries. Output stability: For deterministic workflows, log whether the output changed. If the same input suddenly produces different output, something shifted—model update, retrieval change, or config drift. Detect and investigate. Telemetry and tracing: Instrument the agent loop. Log each step: plan, tool call, observation, next action. Use trace IDs to follow a request through the pipeline. When a user reports a bad response, you can reconstruct exactly what happened. Tracing is essential for debugging agent behavior.",
