			name: "module-12-architecture",
			type: "content-single",
			script: "How do you implement these patterns? Human-in-the-loop approval: Define which actions require approval. When the agent proposes such an action, pause. Present the proposal to a human. Log the request. On approval, execute. On rejection, return feedback to the agent or terminate. The approval gate can be synchronous—wait for human response—or asynchronous—queue for review, notify when ready. For high-volume workflows, use thresholds: auto-approve low-risk, escalate high-risk. Safety policy filter: Before returning output to the user, run it through a filter. Check for harmful content, PII leakage, or policy violations. Block or redact as needed. The filter can be a separate model, a rule-based system, or both. Place it at the output boundary so nothing leaves without a check. Audit trail: Log every significant action. Agent received request. Agent called tool X with args Y. Agent proposed action Z. Human approved. Action executed. Timestamp, user, and outcome. The audit trail supports compliance, debugging, and incident response. In regulated industries, it's mandatory. Store logs in an immutable, append-only system. Transparency and traceability: Users should know when they're interacting with an agent. Disclose that an AI is involved. Provide citations for factual claims. Allow users to see what data the agent used. Transparency builds trust and meets regulatory expectations in many jurisdictions.",
